I came up with several game situations and options for solving them in the form of questions. I put the subject in a game world and a
specific situation and asked him/her to answer how he/she would act if he/she were in the game. I am going to use all the data below to
create game mechanics, story and narrative. It will give an opportunity to be closer to the players if I can show him some familiar and
expected decisions.

user research concluion and other interesting things
One of the most interesting findings is that 3/4 of people
choose a human, not an AI, as a follower. Take into account
that I emphasized that a human can betray or kill you.
Also a very interesting feature is that people are mostly afraid
of lifeless objects like robots, rather than biological mutants.
Most players prefer a diplomatic and puzzling way of solving
problems . Only a small fraction prefer shooting and blowing
things up. This research show that the game will focus on solve
problems through puzzle . But not all .
I invited potential users to write up to 5 items they can take with them to the room they
need to stay in for 1 month. Take into account that the room has basic amenities, toilet,
bed, shower. According this data, I can use these kind of props as a game items, that will
fulfill the expectations of users . Through these items I can tell a story of the game
world, lor and etc
”Some guys wrote that they would take a pillow because it's more comfortable, even though
the room has all the necessary items.”

scenario
Phase: Game mood managemen

Priority: Core
–
Create a game with a balanced mode of meditation and action

U
ser Goal: A simple game where I can pass the time by crafting and riding or solving puzzles and fighting enemies

Scenario


Players have the opportunity to spend time in the game without any difficulty or challenging missions


They can cook food, craft items, fix their car, and drive car in the desert


At the same time, will have to explore abandoned buildings full of dangers such as robots, traps and cannibals .
Ife wants to come home after a hard day and immerse
himself in the game world, forget about all the problems.
Sometimes wants a challenge and rewards for doing it,
sometimes just meditative to do something not tense and
just spend time in another world. 50/50 balance between
challenge and meditation .

V
isceral (how the user wants to feel

She wants to feel safe, to get a good feeling, to get
rewarded for something, to test herself to get equal
emotion dynamic with challenge and relax

Behavioural (what the user wants to do

Wants to learn the hero's story, immerse herself in
another world, experience a sense of danger and then a
sense of release when the danger has passed

R
eflective (who the user wants to be

She wants to be a hero. Wants to make decisions and
overcome her fears

Context: Have an impression from the game, get
satisfaction .

Goals: Ife needs a game where she can clear her head of
the outside world . A mix of relaxation and challenge.

Problems: She doesn't like games that focus on tight
battle timings and skill factors

R
elevant habits: Games, sports, movies .

Demographics: Female, Student, Warsaw, Poland .

mixed scenario
N
orman wants to come home after a hard day and immerse
himself in the game world, forgetting about all his
problems. At his job he performs complex tasks, so when he
turns on the console, he wants to see the result of his
actions, understandable mechanics and just be a part of
the game universe. It's like fishing, when you know you
can catch a fish and you won't leave without a catch.

V
isceral (how the user wants to feel





eflective (who the user wants to be

goal

I conducted 4 interviews and got a lot of information regarding game experience, feelings and painpoints. Most of the
information was written in
R
ussian, because during the interview I had to write down the information as fast as possible
without interrupting the interviewer. And since
R
ussian is my native language, I do it as quickly as possible. I decided
not to translate the notes, as all the following conclusions were made on their basis and written in English.

I also created a questionnaire, in which 140 people participated. On it I focused more on statistical data and tried some
in my opinion, interesting approaches by placing the test subject in a game world, modeling game situations.
